<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-28T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="31" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d31">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 General Committee
                                (Arms)/108: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the American Delegate</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-28T13:00:00-05:00">February 28, 1935—1 p.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>475. Your No. 994, February 27, 5 p.m. We have no objection to the
                                British proposal in regard to governmental credits for exports. Our
                                hesitation was due to doubt as to the effect which our concurrence
                                therein might have upon the attitude of other
                                delegations—particularly the French—toward the Convention. You are
                                authorized to follow your own best judgment in the matter.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>